benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/emails/{accountEmailId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve account email audit logs with history by id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 verifies successful retrieval with status 200, content-type, and expected fields in AuditLog objects.
Empty Response: TC02 and TC18 cover empty results and empty-database responses (empty array and 404 respectively), validating server behavior when no data exists.
Error handling for missing resources: TC03, TC04, TC18, TC19 cover 404 responses for missing account and/or account email.
Input validation / format errors: TC05 and TC06 test invalid accountId/accountEmailId formats and expect 400 responses.
Authentication/Authorization: TC07 and TC08 validate missing and invalid auth tokens (401 Unauthorized).
Downstream/service errors: TC09 and TC12 cover service unavailable (503) and gateway timeout (504) scenarios.
Large dataset / performance: TC11 addresses behaviour with a very large number of audit logs and includes a response-time expectation.
Query parameter tolerance: TC10 exercises the endpoint with an extra query parameter to ensure it still returns expected data.
Security tests: TC13 and TC14 include SQL injection and XSS attempts to validate input sanitization and format rejection.
Ordering & schema regression: TC15 and TC16 verify correct ordering (by changeDate desc) and schema compatibility with AuditLog definition.
Extra state variations: TC02/TC18/TC19 cover several DB state scenarios (no audit logs, empty DB, partially populated DB).
gaps: Pagination: No tests verify pagination behavior (page/limit parameters, pagination headers, correctness when results span multiple pages). TC11 tests a large volume but doesn’t assert paging behavior or limits.
Pagination edge-cases: No tests for boundary values (page=0, limit=0, extremely large page numbers).
Caching Behavior: No tests check caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET handling (If-None-Match / 304 responses).
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests to exercise rate limits, concurrent requests, or expected 429 responses.
Authorization roles / permissions: Tests only cover 401 (unauthenticated) cases; there are no tests for authenticated-but-forbidden (403) scenarios or role-based access control.
500 / Internal Server Error: No explicit tests for generic server errors (500) or how the API surfaces unexpected failures.

Content validation depth: TC01 checks presence of fields but does not validate field types, nested history contents, or complete schema validation in all successful scenarios (though TC16 addresses schema once).
Input boundary and malformed path characters: While there are security inputs, there are no tests for other malformed path encodings (e.g., URL-encoded characters, extremely long IDs).
Rate/throughput performance under load: TC11 has a single response-time expectation but no sustained load or throughput tests.
recommendations: Add explicit pagination tests: verify page/limit query parameters, pagination headers (Link, X-Total-Count), and correct slicing of results; include boundary cases (first/last page, out-of-range pages).
Add caching/conditional GET tests: check ETag and Cache-Control headers, and behavior for If-None-Match / 304 Not Modified responses.
Add rate limiting tests: simulate bursts of requests to validate 429 responses and retry behavior; include exponential backoff guidance.
Add authorization role tests: include scenarios for authenticated users without sufficient permissions expecting 403 Forbidden, and multi-tenant access checks if applicable.
Include server error tests: simulate backend failures to assert 500 Internal Server Error behavior and consistent error payloads.
Extend schema/field validation: add tests that assert types and nested history contents for multiple audit entries, and validate timestamps and changeType enums where applicable.
Add input boundary tests: extremely long IDs, URL-encoded/unsafe characters, and other malformed path variations to ensure robust validation and safe error responses.
Expand performance testing: include load and sustained throughput tests (beyond single large response time) to validate scalability and service-level objectives.
